article.description:
Miami doesn't really care about Rod
Strickland's troublesome past. It's what he's doing now that
matters -- and the Heat couldn't be more pleased with Strickland's
antics these days.
article.headline: Strickland's 23 points help Miami escape Chicago
article.linkText: It's 'Saint Rod' again as Strickland leads Heat
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- Miami doesn't really care about Rod Strickland's troublesome past. It's what he's doing now that matters -- and the Heat couldn't be more pleased with Strickland's antics these days. Strickland scored a season-high 23 points as the Miami Heat held off the Chicago Bulls 92-87 Wednesday night. It was the sixth victory in seven games for Miami, which is just five games below .500 after a horrendous start. "Rod has made a concerted effort to improve his game and stick to the game plan," said Alonzo Mourning, who had 18 points. "Regardless of what everybody has said about Rod Strickland, I've said all year, he's been 'Saint Rod."' Well, that might be pushing it. But without Strickland, Miami would be on its way back home coming off an embarrassing defeat to the Bulls. "He was obviously the catalyst for us," Heat coach Pat Riley said, "driving to the basket, breaking the zone, hitting the outside shots." The Heat had the game all but wrapped up after using a 20-3 run to take a 63-47 lead late in the third quarter. But as it has done with so many opponents this season, Miami let the Bulls back into the game. Midway through the fourth, Travis Best made two free throws and Eddie Robinson connected on a jumper. Marcus Fizer then scored on a hook shot to pull the Bulls to 75-72 with 5:34 to play. Eddie Jones gave the Heat some breathing room, hitting a 3-pointer with four minutes to go. He and Mourning both converted on a pair of free throws, and it seemed like Miami had regained control with an 84-76 lead with 2:38 to play. But the Bulls weren't done yet. Jalen Rose scored on a layup, and Eddy Curry followed with a dunk. Then Rose stole the ball and scored on a fastbreak layup, pulling the Bulls to 84-82 with 1:12 to play. The fans roared, and Rose waved his hands in the air to rev them up even more. Just as quickly, though, Mourning shut them down. He scored on a hook shot, then came up with a huge block of Fizer's layup with 23 seconds left. His free throw with 22 seconds remaining gave Miami an 88-82 lead, and the Heat hung on from there. "Our last few games have been tough," Strickland said. "We didn't play our best tonight, but we won. Any time you do that, it's fun." Rose led Chicago with 23 points, while Travis Best tied his season-high with 18 points. Some of the Bulls weren't happy with the officiating, as Miami took 21 more foul shots (36-15) than Chicago. "It's a tough loss," Rose said. "When you outshoot them and outrebound them and on your home court they outshoot you by like 20 free throws, something is wrong. It was the obvious difference tonight." Actually, the difference was the third quarter. "You are not going to get respect until you get into the playoffs," said Charles Oakley, whose 33 minutes represented his most playing time in two months. "I just want some of my teammates to understand that and stop complaining." After trailing by one at the half, Rose gave Chicago the lead with a jumper at the start of the third quarter. But the Bulls couldn't do much after that. They shot just 24 percent in the quarter -- and it would have been much lower if not for a flurry of shots in the last four minutes. The Heat, on the other hand, got on a roll. Mourning's dunk started the 20-3 run, and Miami was up 63-47 lead with 4:16 left in the third. Strickland scored nine points during the spurt. Chicago went almost seven minutes without a field goal before Rose connected on a 13-footer with 3:57 left. The Bulls ended the quarter with a 9-4 run to set up the fourth-quarter dramatics, but they got started just a little too late. "When you play good teams and get down to them, it is tough to fight back," Bulls coach Bill Cartwright said. "I thought our guys were terrific. We fought back." Game notes
Best was 5-for-5 from the free throw line, extending his streak to 13-for-13 since being traded to the Bulls last month. ... Mourning was 10-for-16 from the free-throw line. ... Bulls rookie Tyson Chandler sat out his third game with a hyperextended little finger, and Cartwright said he doesn't know when the forward will be back. "We're just going to feel it out," he said. "We want to say a week, but we'll just have to see how it goes."
